                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d726">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">817.452/2: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Nicaragua</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Eberhardt</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Managua</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-01-09T13:00:00-05:45"
                            >January 9, 1929—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 3:25 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>16. The Diplomatic Corps held a meeting yesterday to discuss the law referred to
                    in my telegram No. 13, January 7, 3 p.m. I did not attend. They decided not to
                    make any protest at present but simply to transmit direct to their Governments
                    the Foreign Office’s note advising them of the text of the law.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Eberhardt</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
